{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_1lichtenstein_ver02/data/sn83045462/00280601676/1937122801/0170.xml":{"full_text":"THE EVENING STAR\nWith Bondar Merging Edition\nTHEODORE W. NOYES, Editor\nWASHINGTON. D. C.\nTUESDAY....December 28, I9S7\n\u2014---i\nThe Evening Star Newspaper Company\nMain Office: nth St. and Pennsylvania Are.\nNew York Office: 110 Bait aiind St.\nChicago Office: *86 North Ulohlcut Are.\nDelivered by Carrier\u2014City and Suburban\naetalar edition\nEvening and Sunday. i>6c per mo. or ioc per weed\nThe Evening star. 46o rer mo. or loo par waeB\nTba Sunday Star- -6c per copy\nNlkht Final Edition\nNight Pinal and Sunday Star ..7Uc per month\nNight Ping] Star -...66c per month\nCollection made at the end of each month or\neach week. Orders may be sent by mall or tele*\nphone National 1000.\nRate by Mail\u2014Payable in Advance\nMaryland nnd Virginia\nDally and Sunday., l yr. Sio.oui 1 mo. S6o\nDally only-1 yr.. $6.00; 1 mo. 60e\nSunday only-- 1 yr. $4.0C: 1 mo. dOc\nAll Other States and Canadn\nDally and Sunday. 1 yr. S12.00; 1 mo. fl.00\nDally only..1 yr. $8.00: 1 mo. T$a\nSunday only-1 yr. $5.00: 1 mo. 60a\nMember of the Associated Press\n..The Associated Press is exclusively entitles to\ntor republlcatlon of all news dispatches\ncredited to It or not otherwise credited in thle\nPkPer and also tne local news published nereln.\nAil rights of publication of epecial dlepatchee\nherein also ere reserved.\nNeeded, a Goal.\nThe rather frantic manner in which\n\u2022ome New Dealers are seeking to pin the\nbusiness recession of the past few months\non some one, or some group other than\nthemselves, is scarcely convincing. The\nbrilliant and youthful Assistant. Attor\nney General, Robert H. Jackson, Is the\nlatest. His attack is not exactly a nov\nelty\u2014it is on big business. He accuses\nthe monopolists with having priced\nthemselves into a slump.\nThere was a time when New Dealers\nwere chanting the need of higher and\nhigher prices. But that was when the\ncountry was on the way up from a de\npression. It seemed a stupid chant. For\nthe higher the prices, the less the con\nsuming public may consume, the less the\nmanufacturers may manufacture, and\nthe fewer the jobs. On the contrary, when\nprices are comparatively low, the con\nsuming public buys and buys. Now\nthings are different. There is a business\nrecession. No longer do New Dealers say\npridefully \u201cthat is the way we planned\nit.\u201d And now big business is accused of\nraising prices and thereby bringing on\na slump.\nMr. Jackson has advanced a theory\nthat is decidedly New Dealish. He said:\n\"The only way to insure a reasonably\nsteady well-being for the Nation as a\nwhole is for government to act as an im\npartial overseer of our industrial prog\nress, ready at all times to call a halt on\nmonopolistic practices which threaten\nto throw our economy out of order.\u201d\nWhat makes Mr. Jackson believe that the\nGovernment, a political instrument in\ntent upon maintaining itself in power,\ncan or will act as an \u201cimpartial over\nseer\u201d? The attacks which the present\nadministration continues to make upon\nbusiness and industry, its threats of com\npetition with business and industry, are\nnot such as to give the idea that Gov\nernment will be impartial in this matter.\nBut the New Dealers, confronted with\na business recession and the possibility\nof another depression, wish to avoid all\nblame. They have been in control of\nthe Government for approximately five\nyears. They have been given more\npower than any government of this coun\ntry ever was given before. They have\nmixed themselves into the private affairs\nof the American people\u2014as overseers\u2014\nas no government has ever done before.\nThey have discouraged the employment\nof capital through their constant\nthreats of legislation and through their\nhuge expenditures\u2014in private industry.\nAnd so they turn their guns on big\nbusiness, on monopolies, on the news\npapers. They even go to the extent of\nclaiming that business has conspired to\nbring about a recession. They must be\nseeing things in the dark, indeed, if\nthey can imagine business men actually\nseeking to ruin their own business. It\ndoes not make sense. As for news\npapers\u2014they are likely to be the first\nhit by a recession in business. Instead\nof trying to frighten business and the\npublic generally, the effort through\ntheir news columns has been to convey\ngood news, encouraging news. If they\nhave disagreed with some of the eco\nnomic theories of the administration and\nsome of its legislative proposals, they\nhave not hesitated, editorially, to say so.\nBut editorially they have sought to in\nspire confidence, not to destroy it.\nWhen Congress convenes next Mon\nday, there will be a demand from many\nof its members that something be done\nto aid business. Mr. Jackson\u2019s address,\nhowever, coming from an important\nmember of the administration, does not\nIndicate that the Government is to en\ncourage business. Rather does it seem\na forerunner of another attack upon\nbusiness, in an effort to make it appear\nthat the ills of the American people are\nattributable only to business.\nJapanese eloquence in expressing re\ngret is unlimited. It takes much elo\nquence to counterbalance the roar of\ncannon.\nNewton D. Baker was one of the men\nWho did not believe in war, but who was\nnone the less a war hero.\nCows and Spies.\nThe second outbreak of bovine tuber\nculosis within two years in the carefully\nguarded Government herd at Beltsville\ncomes at a time when the question of\nlabor spies is being widely discussed.\nOfficials have voiced the opinion that\nthe trouble in the big Federal experiment\nStation is due to a \"malicious act.\u201d It is\none of those things that just could not\nhappen and yet did.* Forty-four cattle in\nthe herd of 326 animals were found to\nbs Infected, and this in spite of sanitary\nprecautions comparable to those afforded\nhuman beings In a first-class hospital.\nStranger still, this Is the second time\nthe \u201cImpossible\" has happened.\nTwo years ago 80 prize animals were\nvictims and a calf was found, horribly\nbeaten, with a club lying nearby. It was\nonly too obvious that the animals did not\nget that way \u201cnaturally.\u201d Few cattle had\nbeen admitted to the herd and those\nwere carefully tested. For eighteen years\nthe herd had maintained its accredited\nstatus. Despite intensive investigations\nboth outbreaks remain mysteries.\nIt would be unwise public policy, of\ncourse, to reveal the mechanics of the\ninvestigations. It seems logical to sur\nmise, however, that the Government\nplanted agents on the farm in an effort\nto discover the culprit. The agents might\ntruthfully be called by more unpleasant\nterms. It would not be erroneous to label\nthem stool piegons, or labor spies. Un\nder the circumstances popular opinion\nwas with the agents. If there had been\nsuch an organization as the Association\nof Amalgamated Cow Milkers, Beltsville\nLocal, No. 101, protesting the agents\u2019\npresence as \u201cunfair,\u201d it would have\nfound no public support.\nIt is easy to imagine private concerns\nfaced with similar mysteries. Under\nsuch circumstances labor spies are al\nmost indispensable\u2014reprehensible as\nthey may be under more normal condi\ntions. Lawmakers and laymen may\nprofitably give some thought to the\nBeltsville incident before condemning all\nIndustrial espionage too vigorously.\nMr. Hull Back on His Job.\nNow that the nightmare of American\nembroilment in the Far East has been\nbanished, at least for the visible future,\nSecretary Hull is promptly returning to\nhis first love\u2014reciprocal trade agree\nments. According to present indications,\n1938 will be a busy year for him. Since\nthe first pact was concluded with Cuba,\nin 1034, agreements with fifteen other\ncountries have been signed. That is an\nimpressive record. It not only testifies\nto the soundness of the gospel preached\nby the Secretary of State, but attests\nthat the doctrine of economic reciprocity\nas the bedrock of peace is steadily gain\ning adherents in a skeptical world.\nThe United States hopes to negotiate\nno fewer than six additional agreements\nin 1938. Because these would include\npacts with our two biggest customers\u2014\nGreat Britain and Canada\u2014the new year\nis expected to produce the most impor\ntant results yet achieved. Contemplated\narrangements with Canada concern am\nplification of the existing agreement. An\nentirely new deal is in sight with our\nBritish cousins. Besides Canada and\nthe United Kingdom, Secretary Hull\u2019s\nplans look to bargains with Venezuela,\nTurkey, Ecuador and Czechoslovakia.\nThe thorniest paths to be trodden are\nthose leading in the British and Czecho\nslovakian directions. John Bull must\nwatch his tariff step with Uncle Sam\nlest he tread on the toes of the do\nminions, which are active competitors of\nours in the British home market for\nagricultural produce. They naturally\nview with alarm a'ny loss of \u201cempire\npreference\u201d through reciprocal conces\nsions to \"the States.\u201d Czechoslovakia\nseeks in particular tariff favors for her\nimportant footwear industry.\nThroughout four years of campaign\ning for his program, Secretary Hull has\nhad constantly to combat that species of\neconomic human nature which wants\neverybody\u2019s ox gored but its own. While\nstriving to the utmost for a square deal\nfor all concerned, the premier of the\nRoosevelt cabinet rightly and resolutely\nrefuses to be diverted from the goal that\nis immeasurably more important in his\neyes even than ephemerally favorable\ntrade balances\u2014the laying, through mu\ntual trade benefits, of the durable foun\ndations of international accord. Relieved\nof the deadening dread of war and the\nbankrupting burden of competitive ar\nmaments, which it breeds, nations can\nand will devote to the development of\ncommerce the energies they are now\ncompelled to squander on the arts of war.\nThat is the gleaming objective to which\nCordell Hull is dedicating himself with\nTrojan persistence and evangelical zeal.\n\u201cPanay\u201d was mentioned to the Japa\nnese Emperor, who did not admit that\nhe was intimately aware of it. He would\nbe indeed a sorry ruler if he were actually\nas ignorant of men and motives as he\nsometimes assumes to be.\nThere are enough poets in service from\ncoast to coast to make the year of |938\nwonderful for literary art. All we shall\nneed is a few level-headed men to\nwrite the laws by which the people are\nto abide.\nPictures of great politicians are freely\npublished with\u2018a possible intention of\nstimulating an indifference as to what\nmay eventually become of them.\nChina Carries On.\nJapanese guns have demolished Shang\nhai and the Nanking headquarters of\nGeneralissimo Chiang Kai-shek, but\nChina still goes on, and what is more,\ngoes on unconquered.\nHer armies have been beaten before\nand perhaps will be beaten again, but\nno one ever has or ever will conquer her\nterritory that is half again as big as the\nUnited States, her 450 million people,\nher centuries upon centuries of cultural\nheritage which has enabled her to absorb\nany and all who have undertaken to\ndominate her by force of arms.\nNapoleon once called China a \u201csleeping\ngiant\u201d that, when wakened, might soma\nday rule the world. Possibly the \"Little\nCorporal\u201d was partially deceived by ru\nmors, since disproved, of vast resources\nin China, but it is probable that he was\nreferring to the power of absorption by\nwhich China today remains an ethnic\nunit despite centuries of depredations.\nHer conquerors have become Mongols\nand others have become Chinese.\nThere seems, however, at the moment,\nlittle chance at the \"sleeping giant\"\nawakening for a long time to come. Fully\nfour-fifths of the population Is made up\nof peasants and little more than one\ntenth of the land is under cultivation of\nthe most primitive sort. In her principal\nindustry, textile, the domestic system\nstill prevails, according to figures which\nshow that in 1930 the ratio of yarn con\nsumption of the power looms to the hand\nlooms was as one to four. According to\nProfessor J. L. Buck of Nanking Univer\nsity, the Informed consensus is that sev\nenty per cent of China\u2019s industrial output\nboth in quantity and value is from the\ncottage industries.\nIn these days of minimum- wage dis\ncussion in the Capital, a glance at Chinese\nincomes is interesting. The annual in\ncome of the Chinese peasant has been\ncomputed at thirty-five yuan, which\nvaries in terms of our money, but is about\n(9 or $10. More than half of this sum\ngoes for the purchase of food. Accord\ning to figures cited by C. K. Moser of the\nCommerce Department, the Chinese in\ndustrial male worker gets thirty-five\nyuan a month or between $9 and $10,\nwhile the women earn on an average\n11.54 yuan or between $3 and $4 a month.\nWith little beside coal in the way of\nIndustrial resources, it is difficult to see\na world-influencing China, in the eco\nnomic status which now prevails, for\nmany years to come. As far back as two\ncenturies before Christ, a unified China\nunder the Chin Dynasty hurled back the\nnomads of the Urals upon the southeast\nward-migrating Teutonic tribes who fled\nback in terror to the shelter of the Ro\nman Empire and then destroyed it. Who\nis to say a united China may not like\nwise turn upon present-day conquerors?\nThe number of the secretaries simul\ntaneously employed by President Roose\nvelt again calls attention to his effective\nwork in keeping men on the job even\nthough their opinions and methods of\naction may disagree.\nA great many big enterprises are still\ndependent on what A1 Smith may think\nof them, even though his voice may for\nthe present be denied to the arts of\nradio boosting.\nBy studying the letters to Santa Claus,\nit has been disclosed that the children\nof every nationality have all been think\ning the same way.\n\u2018There are many figures to be men\ntioned in connection with traffic toll.\nThose relating to an increasing mortality\nrate will command first consideration.\n\u201cTiny Tim\u201d was again heard from. It\nis unfortunate that Oriental tradition\ndoes not easily submit an analysis of this\nsimple child-type in English literature.\nHoliday greetings are demanded as\nthey come in season. Even the announce\nment of some far-away political \"purge\"\ncannot interfere with them.\nOne effect of interchange with Eastern\nAsia will be to make communications\nbriefer and more readily understood.\nShooting Stars. t\nBY PHILANDER JOHNSON.\nBroadcasting.\nWhen I\u2019m receiving fine advice\nOn what is practical and nice,\nSweet is the song that comes to me\nFrom that big station, \u201cADV.\u201d\nBeethoven, Liszt and Wagner bold\nNew beauties, any night, unfold.\nThey never knew that some fine day\nA part in commerce they might play.\nI listen with respectful care\nFor hints of what to sing or wear.\nEternal genius seems to be\nLinked to that station, \u201cADV.\u201d\nQualification.\n\u201cHow did you come to go into poli\ntics?\"\n\u201cI felt qualified to do so,\u201d answered\nSenator Sorghum. \u201cI heard that a\nstatesman was a politician out of a job.\nAnd I was at least out of a Job.\u201d\nJud Tunkins says however handsome\nthe Christmas card, the handwriting on\nthe envelope means more than the pic\nture inside.\nDistribution of Rest.\nOld Santa swiftly fades from view\nTo sleep beyond the snow.\nI wish Friend Letter Carrier, too,\nCould doze six months or so.\nAll for the Best\n\u201cWhat did you give your husband for\nChristmas?\u201d\n\u201cA patent cigar lighter.\u201d\n\u201cDoes it work?\u201d\n\u201cNo. But it\u2019s all for the best. I\u2019m\nafraid I gave him a box of terrible cigars\nfor Christmas.\u201d\n\u201cHe who knows ill of his neighbor,\u201d\nsaid Hi Ho, the sage of Chinatown,\n\u201cshould keep silent, lest he show how\neasy it may be to have knowledge with\nout wisdom.\u201d\nMovie Luminary.\nTwinkle, twinkle, little star,\nStill we're asking who you are.\nThough your art is small, by thunder,\nYour press agent is a wonder!\n\u201cI 'apises a bad temper,\u201d said Uncle\nEben, \u201cbut I\u2019d rather see a man git mad\ndan be discouraged.\u201d\nStill Gasping.\nProm the Charleston (W. Va.) Mall.\nEvidently the business world didn\u2019t\ncatch its breath during the last breath\ning spell.\nA Successful Pact.\nProm the Paducah (Kr.) Sun-Democrat.\nThe Briand-Kellogg anti-war pact has\nbeen a great success. Since it was signed\nall wars have been undeclared wars.\nA Danger Averted.\nPram the Savannah Nava.\nXmmsdlats danger of being over\nwhelmed by a boom bee beta averted.\nTHE POLITICAL\nMILL\nBY G. GOULD LINCOLN.\nGlenn Frank of Wisconsin has ac\ncepted the invitation of the Republican\nNational Committee\u2019s Executive Com\nmittee to serve as chairman of the Com\nmittee of One Hundred\u2014which has been\nincreased in membership to about two\nhundred. Dr. Frank has an important\ntask on his hands. He is to be the\ndirecting head of a committee which is\nto write a declaration of principles for\nthe G. O. P. Not only must he write\na declaration of principles that will\nsatisfy the progressive as well as the\nconservative groups in the Republican\nparty, but he must please, If he can,\nthose Republicans In Congress like\nSenator McNary, the Republican leader,\nwho would like to have Dr. Frank and\nhis committee say nothing at all. The\nlabors of Hercules were nothing com\npared to this little Job which has been\nlaid In the lap of Dr. Frank.\n\nThe former president of the University\nof Wisconsin, always looked upon as\na liberal, although he did not suit the\nLa Follettes, may succeed, If he does\nthis present Job well, In getting him\nself into a place In the political sun.\nThere has been talk of Dr. Frank as a\ncandidate for Governor of Wisconsin,\nto run against the La Follettes\u2019 candi\ndate In 1938. His one hope of victory\nin such a contest would be to rally the\nDemocrats of the State as well as the\nRepublicans to his support\u2014in other\nwords, a fusion. The chances do not\nlook any too bright.\nThe La Follette Progressives in Wis\nconsin are not only numerous\u2014they\nare clever maneuverers. There Is a\nDemocratic Senator, F. Ryan Duffy,\nfrom Wisconsin who was elected In 1933\nby the grace of the La Follette Pro\ngressives\u2014in those days still a wing of\nthe Republican party in the Badger\nState. In that year the Republicans\nsucceeded in defeating Blaine, the La\nFollette candidate for the senatorial\nnomination. In the primary. They put\nup John B. Chappie, Jr., so the La\nFollette group immediately swung In\nbehind Duffy. That was a bad year for\nthe Republicans anyway, and Duffy won\nalmost two to one.\n\nDuffy comes up for re-election next\nyear. The La Follette Progressives must\nmake up their minds whether they will\nseek both the governorship and the\nSenate seat, or be willing to play ^long\nwith the Democrats, giving them the\nSenate seat and retaining the governor.\nIf the La Follettes think they are strong\nenough, they will go after both places.\nIn that case the Democrats might make\ncommon cause with the Republicans\nand a fusion ticket be placed in the field.\nThe La Follettes, however, have always\nhad the blessing of President Franklin\nD. Roosevelt in their past struggles.\nIn 1934, when Senator Bob La Follette\nwas seeking re-election\u2014this time as a\nProgressive\u2014the President smiled on him\nand turned a cold shoulder to the Demo\ncratic senatorial nominee that year.\nDr. Frank's acceptance of the chair\nmanship of the committee to draft a\nset of Republican principles may mean\nthat he is not considering entering the\ngubernatorial fight\u2014or the reverse. If\nhe had a success, it might put him in\nthe picture for the presidential race in\n1940. There are a great many \"ifs\u201d\nattached to all this.\n\nAccording to dispatches from Wis\nconsin, some of the Republicans there\nare turning interested eyes upon MaJ.\nGen. Douglas MacArthur, who it is re\nported is soon to retire from the Army\nand move back to his old home State.\nNo one seems to know whether Gen.\nMacArthur will be interested in politics.\nBut there are those who would like to\nsee him get into action In Wisconsin,\nbelieving that he would have as dis\ntinguished a career in politics and public\noffice as he has had in the Army. He\nis a young man, still\u2014only 57\u2014and Ls\nretiring, as he has a right to do, after\n40 years Army service.\n\nThe La Follette Progressives, since\nthey set themselves up as an Indepen\ndent progressive party in Wisconsin in\n1934, have been signally successful.\nRepublicans, to whom the La Follette\nregime is anathema, sadly shake their\nheads when they speak about the\nchances of dislodging the La Follettes\nnext year. Senator La Follette continues\nto be a prime favorite of President Roose\nvelt, an active ally of the administra\ntion in the Senate, and Gov. Phil La\nFollette ls believed to be regarded just\nas kindly by the administration. Of\nthe ten members of the House from Wis\nconsin, seven are members of the La\nFollette Progressive party and three are\nDemocrats. Not one of them is Repub\nlican. The political picture in Wisconsin\nis descriptive of what has happened to\nthe once proud G. O. P. in the Middle\nWest. Whether Dr. Glenn Frank and\nhis Committee of One Hundred plus\ncan do anything to change the situa\ntion remains to be seen. It looks as\nthough only a good old ruction in the\nDemocratic party would ever upset the\nnew dealers. And there are those who\nexpect to see just such a battle within\nthe next six months.\n\nFormer Gov. Alf M. Landon of Kansas\nhas stepped Into the limelight very\nfavorably, in the opinion of a number\nof Republican leaders, in the last few\nweeks. They were pleased by his defi\nnite announcement that he would not\nbe a candidate for the presidential nom\nination, which he made here a little\nmore than two weeks ago, when he\ncame to Washington for the December\nGridiron dinner. They were pleased,\ntoo, by the telegram which he sent to\nPresident Roosevelt pledging his aid in\ndealing with the difficult foreign sltuar\ntion. Those who were pleased by his\nrenunciation of any idea of being again\na presidential candidate believed that\nthe party must have a \u201cnew deal\u201d so\nfar as leaders are concerned. They had\nhoped that former President Herbert\nHoover would make an announcement\nsimilar to that of Gov. Landon. It is\ntrue that in his speech In Boston last\nfall, the former President indicated very\nclearly that he had no intention what\never of seeking a presidential nomina\ntion. But what some of the Republicans\ndesire is a statement, definite in every\nway, that Mr. Hoover will not seek or\naccept a nomination. Probably Mr.\nHoover will say nothing more, nor per\nmit himself to be badgered into making\na statement.\nThere is a good deal of undercover\nmaneuvering for control of the Repub\nlican party\u2014leadership\u2014going on. That\nis one of the troubles of the G. O. P.\nToo many are unwilling to submerge\ntheir own personal ambitions for the\nbenefit of the party. It is the excep\ntional politician, however, who is willing\nto make such a sacrifice.\n\nSenator Harry Flood Byrd of Virginia\nfired an opening gun yesterday in the\ncoming battle over the President\u2019s bill\nfor the reorganisation of the executive\ndepartments of the Government. He\nattacked violently the proposal to do\nawaywlto toe Controller General at\ntoo United States\u2014to substitute to his\nA\nTHIS AND THAT I\nBY CHARLES B. TRACEWELL.\n\u25a0uear sir;\n\u201cIt has been thirteen years since I\nhave written you. Remember the young\nfellow that lay abed over the book\nstore?\n\u201cWell, the years have come and that\nsame fellow still lives to praise God.\n\"I found God after many, many years.\n\u201cI found Him in the flower in the\ncrannied wall.\n\u201cI had to search long and hard.\n\u201cBut Jesus said the search was the\npear! of great price.\n\u201cYes, I am well again and flow dad\nand I have a tiny bungalow.\n\n\u201cWhat prompted the letter was a\nrecent article.\n\u201cWe had wondered about a feeder\nfor the birds, when lo! your article.\n\u201cAn old table was found in the cellar,\nstrips of wood were put on the edge\nto hold the food from falling off, many\npine boughs were put around it to form\na perfect screen, leaving only the front\nopen.\n\u201cOn the table were piled sunflower\nseeds, scratch feed (fine) and sand.\n\u201cI wish you might peep out there\nright now. I never knew that the\ntufted titmouse loved sunflower seeds\nbefore.\n\"The branches are full of birds.\n\u201cRed birds, snow birds, black capped\ntitmice, tufted titmouse, wood sparrows,\nthe nuthatches, Jays, the woodpeckers\nand a wren.\n\"We thank you for telling of this\nsimple feeding station. We put out\nsome suet in a cloth bag that comes\nwith the oranges. How they do enjoy\na peck at it!\n\u201cThanks for your articles.\n\u201cYour friend that still loves to take\na trip with Conrad over the South Seas.\n\u201cCordially, C. W. 8.\u201d\n\nAn old table, a soap box, a board,\nor even a patch of earth, makes a very\ngood feeder.\nThe food, not the feeder, is the essen\ntial thing.\nAnything, or nothing, almost, will do\nfor a device.\nWhat is in the device is what counts.\nIt is essential for all persons who\nthink that they might like to feed the\nbirds, but who have not yet done so,\nto remember that it is the food, and\nnot the gadget, which is of importance.\nWhen stress is thus laid on foods,\nthe enthusiast who gives good advice\nwould hope to avoid giving the idea\nthat bird food, in its turn, is a very\ncomplicated matter.\nNeither feeder nor feed need worry\nany one.\nA bare spot of ground, or a sidewalk,\nwill do for the \"feeder\u201d; breadcrumbs\nwill help many a starving, and there\nfore freezing, bird.\n\nYet there is no gainsaying that a\nsimple feeder, such as discussed by our\ncorrespondent, adds something to the\nsport.\nUsually it is well within the means\nor ability of any one.\nAmericans, as a nation, are gadget\nminded.\nThey like to make things, and to use\nthem when made.\nThat was the pioneer spirit, and it\nis still the spirit of our land.\nr-\nWhat would have become of Christmas\ngiving.If It hadn\u2019t been for our enthu\nsiasm for gadgets of one sort or another?\na\nYet the food Is the Important thing,\nwhether it la bread, crusts, suet, fancy\nseed, peanuts, or whatnot.\nGoing along the other day, we saw\na sidewalk covered with birds.\nOut of an apartment window some\none had scattered sunflower seeds and\ncracked com.\nEnglish sparrows and pigeons com\nposed the bulk of the consumers.\nWhat a happy time they were having 1\nIt was as fine a Christmas picture\nas one could want to see, but no doubt\nhundreds of pedestrians failed to see It.\nIndeed, practically all the walkers\nthere scattered the birds, preventing\nthem from eating.\na a\nThe diners did not mind that, though.\nAs soon as pedestrians passed, the\nsparrows and others flew back.\nThey enjoyed every grain.\nSuch Impromptu feasts mean as much\nto the birds as if they dine at the most\ncleverly constructed \u201cbird feeder.\"\nWe hope that many of these clever\ngadgets were received as Christmas\npresents.\nThere are many types of feeders, some\nof them inclosed with glass. Some are\non wires, some on poles, others on\nstakes.\nSome are to be placed on trees.\nSome feeding devices are for use on\nwindowsills.\n\nIt seems particularly appropriate that\nmany people will take up bird feeding\nas the result of Christmas gifts of feeders\nand seed.\nFrom now on comes the hardest time\nof the year for those birds which choose\nto winter in this vicinity.\nNot for them the warmer reaches of\nthe Southland! They prefer to stay\nwhere It Is cold.\nLong stretches of snow on the ground\ncut off their supply of food, unless people\ncome to their rescue.\nIt should be kept In mind by every\nnewcomer to this combined sport and\ngood deed that once begun it should\nbe continued, for the birds come to\nlook for food where they have re\nceived it.\n\nEven persons who do not choose to\nfeed them continuously will be doing\na good thing by remembering them In\nfreefing weather, especially In snowy\ntimes.\nThen they are deprived of food ex\ncept such berries as they may find\non shrubs.\nIt can be imagined that the berries\nare pretty well picked over by the time\nthe severest weather comes.\nSnow covers lawns and even weeds\non vacant ground. The latter consti\ntute a large part of such \u201cever-normal\ngranary\u201d as the wild birds enjoy In\nwinter.\nIt is necessary to make up to them\nfor this deficit, and handfuls of cracked\ncom, wheat, bread, suet, sunflower and\nother seeds, nuts, even fruits, help im\nmensely.\nA cut apple gives them both food\nand drink.\nSTARS, MEN AND ATOMS\nNotebook of Science Progress in Field,\nLaboratory and Study.\nBY THOMAS R. HENRY.\nDoes a microbe have brains?\nEvidence for the existence of a nerv\nous system with a motor center in cer\ntain groups of protozoa\u2014the microscopic,\nsingle-celled creatures at the bottom of\nthe animal kingdom\u2014is summed up by\nDr. R. Ralph Fowell of King\u2019s College,\nLondon, in a report to the Royal Micro\nscopical Society.\nIn some of the larger animals of this\ngreat family extremely minute fibrils\ncan be detected which contract when\nthe creature moves. They seem to run\ntoward a common center, or motorium.\nMoreover, all seem to act in harmony\nso that the whole body co-operates in\nthe movement. One part doesn\u2019t pull\nagainst another.\nApparently these fibrils serve one of\ntwo purposes\u2014they may be beginning\nof a cellular structure or the earliest\nappearance of nerves, through the pos\nsession and perfection of which in multi\ncelled creatures animal life has made\nsuch remarkable progress. Or at this\nstage of life nervous system and skeleton\nmay be the same.\nSome weight is given to the nerve\nhypothesis by the sensitivity shown by\nsome of these protozoa to such drugs\nas atropine, aconite and caffeine, which\nact specifically as nerve poisons in\nhigher animals, leaving other tissue un\naffected. However, other groups of pro\ntozoa which seem to have equally de\nveloped fibril systems are relatively un\naffected by the poisons. It may be that\nat some stage these fibrils change from\nskeletal to nervous.\nThe remarkable co-ordination that\nexists in body movements of these one\ncelled creatures, Dr. Fowell points out,\nalmost necessitates the assumption of\nsome regulating mechanism, such as is\nfurnished by the nervous system in\nhigher animals. But such a co-ordinat\ning motorium would constitute a form\nof brain. The primary object of the brain\nwas to govern movement, and all Its other\nfunctions seem to have arisen, by va\nrious processes of refinement, out of this.\nThe motorium of the microbe, how\never, hardly can be considered as a\nprimitive brain of the type which has\nreached a higher development in many\ncelled animals from sponges to men.\nThe latter has been produced by a\ndifferentiation of cells. In the protozoan\nthe controlling mechanism had to be\nproduced by a differentiation of material\nwithin a single cell. The possibilities\nare infinitely more limited.\n\nAbout 260,000,000 years ago most of\nthe Northern Hemisphere enjoyed a\nsemi-tropical climate. Forests grew lux\nuriantly as far north as Greenland. It\nwas during this period that the great\ncoal deposits were laid down.\nplace an Auditor General\u2014and to take\naway the right of Congress to have this\nofficer pass first upon the legality of\nexpenditures made by the executive de\npartments. As the law now stands, the\nController General decides whether\nexpenditures are being made in accord\nance with the law\u2014before the money is\npaid. That is a check which Congress\nspecifically set up on Government spend\ning, and the Controller General was\nmade responsible to Congress, rather\nthan to the President. This has not\npleased the New Deal Administration,\nalthough the previous administrations\nhad been able to get along well enough\nwith the Controller General. The\nreorganisation bill is due to come up In\nthe Senate as soon as the anti-lynching\nbill has been disposed of\u2014whenever that\naaay be.\nAt the same time the lands now\ncrossed by the equator were covered\nwith ice. Typical glacial boulders are\nfound there today, scratched like those\nborne by the modem ice sheets of Green\nland and the Antarctic. It was, the\ngeological evidence indicates, the most\ntitanic glaciation the world ever has\nknown. The area covered was much\nvaster than that of North America,\nEurope and Asia covered with glaciers\nin the last ice age.\nStrangest of all, as pointed out by\nDr. W. W. Watts, British geologist, in\nthe annual report of the Smithsonian\nInstitution, the direction of this titanic\nglaciation was southward, from the\npresent equator toward the South Pole.\nThis leads him to the hypothesis that\nthe equatorial lands then were actually\nat the South Pole.\nOne explanation has been that the\naxis of the earth has shifted so that\nwhat is now the South Pole may have\nbeen approximately at the equator in\ncarboniferous times. But a little con\nsideration shows this to have been im\npossible. The Northern Hemisphere\nwould have been affected as well as\nthe Southern. There would have been\na northward movement of glaciers.\nMoreover, it is impossible to postulate\nsuch an immense shifting of the earth\u2019s\naxis in geological time.\nThe alternative hypothesis proposed\nby Dr. Watts is that the glaciated lands\nformed parts of a single land mass\nduring carboniferous times and that\nthis mass floated like a raft across the\nSouth Pole. The glaciation actually\nwas from the south northward, but the\nlands themselves have been turned\naround in the great time interval that\nfollowed.\nThis land mass, Dr. Watts says, would\nhave been the hypothetical ancient con\ntinent of Gondwanaland, long since split\nup into fragments such as South Africa,\nthe southern part of South America,\nMadagascar, Australia, New Zealand,\nthe present Antarctica and the Falk\nland Islands.\nOverstocked.\nFrom the Worcester Oozette.\nA serious problem has arisen in post\nseason football discussion. There were\nabout 5,000 varsity players in action, or\napproximately half enough to supply the\nvarious all-America teams.\nNo Penalty for Thinking.\nProm the Cleveland Plain Dealer.\nUp in Detroit a woman who socked a\ndeputy collector of internal revenue is\nfined $50. They can't do anything to\nyou for thinking, though, while making\nout your income tax return.\nProfitless.\nFrom the Hartford Tlmei.\nWhat will it profit women to own\nmost of the country\u2019s wealth if men own\nthe cosmetic factories?\nThe Favorite.\nFrom the Bridgeport Tlmee-Btar.\nWe don\u2019t care who runs for President\nin 1940. We\u2019ve already made up our\nmind to vote for Charlie McCarthy.\nHomer Up to Date\nFrom the cAand bland independent.\nHousewife\u2019s Odyssey: To market, to\nmarket, to buy a thick steak; home\nagain, hems again with eodfUh or hake.\nANSWERS TO\nQUESTIONS\nBY FREDERIC J. HASKIN.\nA reader con get the answer to any\nQuestion of lad by writing The Evening\nStar Information Bureau, Frederic J.\nHaskin, director, Washington, D. C.\nPlease inclose stamp for reply.\nQ. How many greeting cards are sent\nat Christmas time by the American\npeople?\u2014L. D.\nA. There are no reliable figures. It\nIs estimated that the number may run\nto 200,000,000.\nQ. Are women more apt to prejure\nthemselves on the witness stand than\nmen, as Schopenhauer believes?\u2014L. J.\nA. Judge Joseph Sabbath, the famous\ndivorce magistrate, summing up his\ngeneral estimate on women, says: \u201cThe\nmajority of women have never been In\nthe courtroom before. Naturally, al\nthough they are a bit nervous and em\nbarrassed when questioned, they reply\ndirectly and honestly.\u201d Former Assist\nant Attorney General Mabel Willebrandt\nsays that \u201cwomen make good and reli\nable witnesses or not, depending upon\ntheir clarity of speech, simplicity of\nthought and ability to quick compre\nhension, the same as men They\narfi accurate and honest If their mem\nories and intentions are good\u2014Just like\nmen.\u201d\nQ. How long Is the Potomac River?\n\u2014S. H.\nA. It is about 450 miles long.\nQ. Are finger nails thicker near the\nroots or at the ends?\u2014S. T.\nA. They are thickest at the outer\nends.\nQ. Is there a law in Washington, D. C.,\nabout how coal must be sold?\u2014C. F.\nA. In Washington, D. C., the law\nrequires that coal be sold by the long\nton. Consumers In that city get a full\n2,240 pounds when they buy a ton of\ncoal.\nQ. Is It dangerous to drink milk and\neat fish at the same meal?\u2014R. W. H.\nA. As long as the foods are fresh\nand in good condition, there Is no risk\nin combining them at the same meal.\nOne of the best known authorities on\nnutrition says that any foods which\nmay safely be eaten separately may\nsafely be eaten together.\nQ. How long has the term, cold wave,\nbeen used?\u2014C. E.\nA. The United States Weather Bureau\nfirst used the term in 1872, applying\nit to the areas of cold, clear, dry air\nthat flow from Canada southward. The\nrate of progress of the front of a cold\nwave is so steady and uniform that\nterritory in its path can b\u00ab warned\nbeforehand.\nQ. What is the most abundant species\nof fox?\u2014W. H.\nA. It is the red fox. found over most\nof Canada and the United States.\nQ. How long have sunspota been\nobserved on the sun?\u2014K. 8. M.\nA. The sunspot cycle of 11 y2 years,\napproximately, has been identified\namong the weather records left in trees\nand in ancient rocks. This seems to\nprove that whatever causes the varia\nbility of the sun. it has been varying\nJust as it does now for perhaps a billion\nyears.\nQ. How many people perished in\nFrance during the Reign of Terrorr\n\u2014A3.\nA. Between September, 1793 and July.\n1794, about 3,000 people were executed\nin Paris, and at least 15,000 in other\nparts of France.\nQ. Please give some information\nabout the new air terminal in Ger\nmany.\u2014A. L. M.\nA. The first section of what will be\nthe largest air terminal in the world\nhas been started at Tempelhof Air\nfield, Berlin. The air terminal will be\nbuilt in the style of New York railroad\nterminals, and is to be three-quarters\nof a mile long. A seven-story office\nbuilding will surmount the central hall.\nTerraces on the roof of the terminal\nand adjoining hangars will provide seats\nfor 100,000 spectators at air games. The\nflying field will be three times the size\nof the present one. The project will\nbe completed in 1939.\nQ. Was Anne Boleyn beautiful?\n\u2014W. R.\nA. She is described as \u201cnot one of\nthe handsomest women in the world,\nof a middling stature, with swarthy\ncomplexion, a long neck, wide mouth,\nbosom not much raised, and in fact,\nhas nothing but the English King s great\nappetite, and her eyes which are black\nand beautiful and take great effect.\u201d\nQ. Is there an active rocket society?\n\u2014J. M.\nA. There are at least two. The Amer\nican Rocket Society has about 350 mem\nbers in all parts of the world. Almost\nall important experimenters in this line\nare members. The other large group\nis the British Interplanetary Society,\nwhich has about 100 members.\nFollow the \u201cWar\u201d\nWith a Good Map.\nBetween fighting and apologizing for\nshooting the wrong people, Japan is hav\ning a lively time in China. Keep up with\nthe news frem Asia. Oet a good map\nshowing the latest boundaries, with the\naccepted spellings, so that you can readi\nly follow the news dispatches. Asia is\nplaying an Important part in world af\nfairs. Half of the- people of the world\nlive there. America has important in\nterests that must be respected. On the\nreverse side of this new map is a mass\nof statistical data of general Interest.\nSend for your copy today. Inclose 10\ncents to cover cost and handling.\nUse This Order Blank\nThe Washington Evening Star\nInformation Bureau,\nFrederic J. Haskln, Director,\nWashington, D. C.:\nI Inclose herewith TEN CENTS In\ncoin (carefully wrapped) for a copy\nof the MAP OP ASIA.\nName\nStreet or Rural Route\nCity\nState\n(Please erder by mall only.)","height":"31292","width":"22584"}}
